*** Introduction
	Punishing criminals has been well-understood as essential in a functioning
	society where safety is cherished. Most societies enforced their laws by
	sending their dissidents into prisons, others have sympathized with the
	criminals as a product of their environment deserving to be given another
	chance. Both approaches towards criminals have been seen throughout history
	in some form or the other with untrackable potential effectiveness due to
	the complexity of this problem; as one can not simply send a person to
	prison stealing years from his life. Neither can one let them be a free
	threat to society.
	
*** Paragraph 1
	Traditionally, authorities sent their outlaws to prisons selecting them out
	of society. A serial killer is a serious threat to everyone, by enforcing
	merciless prison sentences, offenders are erased from society. The rationale
	being that felons of high calibre have innate inclination towards harming
	others. This punishment was effective in removing unwanted actions in a
	country and maintaining trust in justice for the victim's families by
	removing repeated criminals. In result, in long term, future criminals are
	scared away from criminal career producing a safe society.
	
*** Paragraph 2
