* <2022-01-25 Tue> Task Paper: 9093/22 Feb/March 2021 Section B Question 4
** Ideas
	+ Reasons why many teenagers are not interested in the news
	  1) They don't feel it affects them
	  2) They don't understand what is happening politically
		 + Historical illiteracy
	  3) Lack of argumentative skills in order to discuss sensitive issues
	  4) They are not given the chance by adults to give their opinions
	  5) Teenagers tend to follow more political news sources caused by the
		 increase in use of social media and it's effects
	  6) Teenagers tend to be rejecting tradition and culture in favor of more
         modern ideologies.
		 + use previous points to feed into this
*** Hypothesis
	Teenagers are not interested in traditional news, where politically charged
	news have replaced unbiased investigative reporting.
*** Thesis
	This composition aims at finding to what extent this is the case.
** Text
*** Hypothesis
	Teenagers are introduced to the internet of things from a very young age,
	where everyone comes together from different walks of life capable to
	discuss current affairs and issues. Unfortunately, this is exactly in
	contrast to what is happening. Adolescent teens are giving up traditional
	investigative journalism in favor of more radical opinionated news sources.
	This change in news intake sources is contributable to a multitude of
	lifestyle shortcomings in the average teenagers' life.
*** Thesis
	This composition aims to investigate issues that contribute to the radical
	change in news intake for teenagers.
*** Paragraph 1
	"People who do not understand politics are controlled by who do" is a common
	quote thrown around in political circles. This message is not understood by
	the young. Adolescents are quick to zone out when current affairs are
	discussed; "Why should I care?", "It doesn't effect me" are fallacies of a
	fallen youth. The necessity for teenagers to understand events and changes
	around them is essential in maintaining a free society. Although small
	policy changes may not seem interesting, accumulated change could cause
	radicalization of culture.
*** Paragraph 2
	Interest in news is only half of the issue. Interest in news without correct
	interpretation or formation of opinion is useless. Teenagers fill their time
	gossiping about the latest video-game released or their idol's last meal.
	This wasted time was used by elder generations acquainting themselves with
	George Orwell's Animal Farm or Ray Broadbary's 481 Fahrenheit, at the time
	relevant novels inspired from current world-affairs. This lack of
	interpretation skills is another reason why teenagers feel left out when
	adults discuss current news in informal settings.
*** Paragraph 3
	Teenagers are increasingly anti-social by nature. They lack argumentative
	skills to assist them in discussions about current news. New ideas and
	points of views are more attractive to teenagers; adolescents may adopt
	these views only to find themselves incapable of sharing their ideas. The
	lack of skill is further fostered by failure from schools to incentivize
	free debates and encouraging students to defend their positions against
	opposition. This incapability of discussion causes them to retreat into
	disengagement and immediate disapproval of mainstream news.
*** Paragraph 4
	Lack of skills and independent thought is very common in adolescent years.
	That coupled with lack of historical knowledge makes it very easy for adults
	to dismiss and discourage contribution in informal settings where news is
	discussed. Although it is true that teenagers may by incapable to engage
	effectively in adult-talk, they only can stumble to truth. If teenagers
	decide to incorporate new-age hippie opinions on current affairs, it would
	benefit everyone to let them stand in truth's court fighting for their views
	and hopefully increasing their interest in news and political talk.
*** Paragraph 5
	Young individuals are more technically literate, spending their time
	scrolling through social media. On these platforms, political news are much
	more favored than investigative reporting news channels. The prevalence of
	political news sources is attributed to the design of these social media
	platforms /and/ teenagers natural inclination towards radical views. This
	combination of radical opinions and adolescence creates a more radically
	polarized youth. Although this is only a loud minority, more and more
	teenagers are following non-traditional forms of news
*** Paragraph 6
	The rejection of tradition and culture is a common "feature" of young
	thought. Ignorance of the importance of keeping up-to date with current
	affairs with incapability of sharing ideas contribute to an increased
	interest in radical news channels. The digitized exchange of information
	made it very easy to subscribe to radical ideologies. The youth is more
	interested in news sources that give biased reporting of events than
	investigative news.
*** Conclusion
	Although teenagers may seem that they are less engaged in news, it is
	nothing further from the truth. These digital citizens get their news from
	modern methods of delivering current world-affairs. The platforms of which
	these opinions are forced on addicted teenagers are designed to foster
	adolescent thought. This cultural change from investigative journalism into
	opinionated thought is done by people who understood politics and imposed
	change on people who didn't.
* <2022-02-02 Wed> Task Paper: 9093/13 May/June 2021 Section A Question A
** Text
   Fellow Truth-Seekers,

   We all have seen "organic-produce" labels in super-markets. We heard how good
   they are in schools, news and even that crazy tin-foil hat uncle said it is
   good in family gatherings. But does organic food truly live up-to it's name?
   After all, I don't taste any difference!

   Organic farming is more than food, it is a philosophical ideal, a rejection
   of modern industrialization and an attempt to return back to our natural
   roots. Organic foods signifies an ideal, a healthy lifestyle - moral
   superiority.

   As you probably know, theoretical ideals don't always port well into
   practice. The fact is, regulatory bodies fail about half the time to detect
   in-organic procedures in mislabeled produce. Furthermore, companies are
   incentivized to meet market demand of organic food, this usually ends up with
   organic labels on artificially made food - who thought cereal can be organic?

   We stand divided seeking truth, let this debate session commence!

* <2022-02-03 Thu> Task Paper: 9093/13 May/June 2021 Section A Question B
** Text
   The form of the original text is a blog post, where the author discusses his
   opinion on organic food as over-rated from the perspective of psychology to
   an educated audience.

   The text begins with an authoritative tone expressing shortcoming in "how we
   perceive flavor" using statistical data such as "8% of men...". The first
   three paragraphs do not seem linked to the purpose of the text until later
   on.

   The third paragraph on-wards, there is a constant shift from persuasive tone
   and authoritative. In the former, the writer uses personal pronouns that
   address the reader directly. While other paragraphs use formal reporting tone
   in order to convey facts.

   In contrast, the opening speech starts with explaining the topic. The speaker
   uses informal language to address the class. The rhetorical sentence
   "after-all" builds trust between the speaker and the audience, appropriate
   for an opening speech in a classroom.

   Unlike the first text, the speech stays neutral by first addressing points
   for organic food such as "moral-superiority" by returning to "our natural
   roots". The third paragraph addressing opposing points. Paragraph 2 and 3
   have an authoritative tone as they address talking points for the debate.
* <2022-02-03 Thu> Task Paper: 9093/11 Oct/Nov 2021 Section B
** Text
   The open letter's purpose is to be comforting, relatable and authoritative
   towards the subject of happiness. Richard uses meek, indirect and informal
   tone to address his audience of the general populace of stressed people. he
   achieves his purpose by using a letter text structure with short paragraphs,
   coupled with a variety of language devices: pronouns, triplet nouns, and
   anaphora.

   The writer builds trust with the reader in the first paragraph by explicitly
   mentioning his intentions of being "open and honest". he accomplishes this
   connection by using personal pronouns like "You" and "I".

   Richard uses his trust to comfort the reader by starting paragraph 2 by using
   noun triplets: "stressed, scared and sad". he uses phrases' such as "failed
   in business" "minced ..." in order to seem relatable to the reader and convey
   a sense of understanding towards the reader's misery.

   The writer shifts his tone in the 4th paragraph into indirect confrontation,
   and his audience in third-person. he addresses the same stressed audience
   using "they" while pointing out their mistakes. This indirect confrontation
   maintains the meek tone of the general text.

   In the 5th paragraph, the writer relates to the reader's youth by using the
   noun "Kids" and reminding the audience of order they got, "go to school" "go
   to college". he uses anaphora to depict the importance of the shortcomings of
   how as kids we are told to be happy.

   The writer describes his experience in building a "business empire",
   attending "memorable parties" as bringing "great joy". He only uses the noun
   phrase "true happiness" when addressing "just...be" happiness. This subtle,
   yet apt choice of nouns hones-in the topic of the letter, authentic
   happiness.

   The writer frequently uses the structural devices of short sentences such as:
   "Try it." "Stop and breathe.". This generous use of short sentences embodies
   the grandiose subject of the text - living in the moment. 

   The writer uses multiple short phrase listings with anaphora in paragraph 8
   in order to remind the reader of the small stuff that inspires happiness. The
   paragraph begins with the use of the pronoun "me". This shows the reader
   Richard's authenticity towards the subject.
